    <div class="lesson-content-body">
        <div class="lesson-content-memo">Some nuclides decay</div>
        
        <div class="col-md-7 col-lg-7">
        There are several terms which all mean 'radioactive nuclide': 
        <strong>radionuclide, radioisotope</strong>, and <strong>radioactive isotope</strong>.
        
        Radionuclides vary in:
        <ul>
            <li><strong>radioactive decay mode</strong>(s) exhibited, (<strong>&#945;,&#946;,&#947;</strong>)</li> 
            <li>the probability that each mode will occur</li>
            <li>the <strong>energies</strong> of radiation produced </li>
            <li><strong>decay rate</strong> (related to the half-life - the time for half a population of
                nuclides to decay)</li>
            <li><strong>origin</strong> (natural, artificial)</li>
        </ul>    
            Some examples of unstable nuclides:
